      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31992,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D) Dengue </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option D:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Dengue fever is a <strong>viral illness </strong>transmitted by <strong>Aedes mosquitoes. </strong>Unlike some of the other diseases listed, routine screening for Dengue in donated blood is not typically performed. This is because<strong> Dengue is primarily transmitted by mosquitoes rather </strong>than through<strong> blood transfusions.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option A.</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong> Malaria </strong>is routinely screened for in <strong>donated blood </strong>because it is caused by <strong>parasites transmitted through the bite of infected mosquitoes</strong>. <strong>Screening helps </strong>prevent<strong> </strong>the transmission of<strong> malaria </strong>through <strong>blood transfusions</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option B.</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">&nbsp; <strong>Hepatitis B </strong>is a<strong> viral infection </strong>that can be transmitted through <strong>blood transfusions. </strong>Screening for <strong>Hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) </strong>is essential to prevent the transmission of the<strong> virus to recipients of donated blood</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option C.</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong> Screening for HIV </strong>is crucial in <strong>donated blood to prevent the transmission of the virus to recipients</strong>. HIV screening typically involves testing for<strong> antibodies to HIV-1 and HIV-2</strong>, ensuring the<strong> safety of the blood supply</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Educational objective: </span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">While diseases such as <strong>HIV, Hepatitis B, and Malaria </strong>are routinely screened for in <strong>donated blood to ensure the safety of the blood supply</strong>,<strong> Dengue is not </strong>typically included in routine <strong>screening protocols </strong>as it is primarily transmitted by<strong> mosquitoes rather than through blood transfusions</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>",
