      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Most common blood transfusion reaction is:</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3760812",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31993,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. A) Febrile non-hemolytic transfusion reaction </span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">FNHTR is the <strong>most common</strong> type of transfusion reaction. It is characterized by <strong>fever, chills, and rigors without</strong> evidence of <strong>hemolysis. </strong>It is usually caused by a reaction between the<strong> recipient&#39;s immune system and leukocytes </strong>in the transfused blood.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. Hemolysis: </span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">it </span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">is a<strong> serious but less common </strong>transfusion reaction. It occurs when <strong>red blood cells are destroyed, </strong>leading to the release of<strong> hemoglobin into the bloodstream</strong>. Hemolysis can be caused by <strong>various factors, </strong>including <strong>ABO incompatibility, improper storage</strong>, or<strong> bacterial contamination</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Transmission of Infections: </span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">While the transmission of infections is a<strong> serious concern in blood transfusions, </strong>it is <strong>not the most common </strong>transfusion reaction.<strong> Stringent screening and testing procedures for donated blood </strong>have significantly <strong>reduced </strong>the risk of<strong> transmitting infections, </strong>making FNHTR more common.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D.</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Electrolyte Imbalance: </strong>Electrolyte imbalances are <strong>not </strong>a common transfusion reaction. However, in some cases, <strong>transfusions with large volumes of blood or specific blood components </strong>can lead to <strong>electrolyte disturbances</strong>. This is <strong>not the primary </strong>or most common transfusion reaction.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;Most common<strong> blood transfusion </strong>reaction is <strong><span style=\"color:black\">Febrile non-hemolytic transfusion reaction.</span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref:</span></span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"> Robbins 10<sup>th</sup> 667 </span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
