          "id": 61596,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Metabolic alkalosis</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 61597,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Metabolic acidosis </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 61598,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Respiratory alkalosis </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 61599,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Respiratory acidosis</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"background-color:white\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">A 40-year-old male involved in a motor vehicle collision requires a massive transfusion due to severe hemorrhagic shock. He receives 15 units of packed red blood cells within a 24-hour period. </span></span></span><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Which of the following complications is likely to result after several units of blood have been transferred?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3823748",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31994,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. A) Metabolic alkalosis </span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Option A:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\"><strong>Metabolic alkalosis </strong>is a common complication after a <strong>massive transfusion due to the metabolism of citrate,</strong> which is used as an <strong>anticoagulant in stored blood</strong>, into<strong> bicarbonate</strong>.<strong> Lactate</strong>, which may accumulate in <strong>stored blood due to hypoperfusion and anaerobic metabolism</strong>, is also <strong>converted to bicarbonate </strong>when<strong> normal perfusion is restored</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Option B. Metabolic acidosis:</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\"> While metabolic acidosis can be present initially <strong>due to hypoperfusion and lactic acidosis</strong>, the administration of several units of blood typically results in the correction of the acidosis, <strong>potentially overshooting into alkalosis </strong>due to the reasons mentioned above.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Option C. Respiratory alkalosis:</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\"> Respiratory alkalosis typically results from <strong>hyperventilation, </strong>which may occur in patients in<strong> pain or with anxiety</strong>, but it is not directly related to the transfusion of blood products.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Option D. Respiratory acidosis:</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\"> Respiratory acidosis is caused by <strong>hypoventilation and the accumulation of carbon dioxide </strong>in the blood. It is not a common complication associated with blood transfusion itself, unless there are<strong> underlying respiratory issues or transfusion-related complications affecting lung function.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong><strong> </strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Massive Transfusion </span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">is defined as the need to transfuse from<strong> one to two times the patient&rsquo;s normal blood vol&shy;ume</strong>. In a normal adult, this is equivalent to <strong>10-20 units</strong>. Most common abnormality is <strong>metabolic alkalosis</strong>. It re&shy;sults from conversion of<strong> citrate (present in stored blood) and lactate (accumulated due to hypoperfusion) to bicar&shy;bonate.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref:</span></span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"> Robbins 10<sup>th</sup>/ 668 </span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
