      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31996,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. C) O positive RBC and colloids/crystalloid </span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option C:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Selection of blood for emergency transfusion </span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">If patient&rsquo;s blood group is known, </span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">unmatched blood group of the same group may be used. </span></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">If the patient&rsquo;s blood cannot be determined, </span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Group O red blood cells </strong>should be chosen. The use of such<strong> unmatched blood should be Rh (&ndash;ve) </strong>when used in woman of child-bearing age in whom we do not want sensitization to Rh antigen. As Rh-negative blood is often in limited supply, <strong>Rh positive blood </strong>is used in the<strong> emergency transfusion of older females and males of unknown blood group</strong>. In such cases <strong>sensitization may occur </strong>but the<strong> risk of an immediate hemolytic reaction is low</strong>. <strong>O blood group </strong>is the <strong>universal donor </strong>and therefore, should be given to this patient. </span></span></span></span>\r\n\t<ul style=\"list-style-type:circle\">\r\n\t\t<li><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">positive RBCs and colloids/crystalloid:</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"> In emergencies where the blood type is unknown or cannot be confirmed, it is standard to use <strong>O positive RBCs for males and older females </strong>because of the<strong> availability and lower risk </strong>of causing an <strong>immediate hemolytic reaction</strong>.<strong> Colloids or crystalloids </strong>can be used to<strong> maintain volume</strong>.</span></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t</ul>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option A. RBCs corresponding to his red cell group and colloids/crystalloid:</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"> While it might seem intuitive to use RBCs corresponding to his red cell group, in cases where there is a <strong>discrepancy and the patient&#39;s blood group cannot be confirmed, </strong>it is <strong>safer to use group O RBCs, </strong>which are considered <strong>universal donors</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option B. Whole blood corresponding to his plasma group:</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"> When the ABO group cannot be determined, using whole blood of a specific group is<strong> not recommended </strong>due to the risk of an<strong> ABO incompatibility reaction</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option D. AB negative whole blood:</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"> AB negative blood is considered the<strong> universal plasma donor</strong>, <strong>not the universal RBC donor</strong>. This option could result in an<strong> ABO incompatibility reaction if the patient is not AB negative.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong> </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>O positive RBCs </strong>can be used in <strong>males and non-childbearing potential females, with colloids or crystalloid solutions </strong>to manage volume, as this approach<strong> minimizes </strong>the risk of<strong> hemolytic transfusion reactions</strong>. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref:</span></span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"> Wintrobes 12<sup>th</sup> 836</span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
