        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. D) Cryoprecipitate </span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option D:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Cryoprecipitate is prepared from <strong>FFP by cold precipitation </strong>and contains a<strong> high concentration </strong>of specific coagulation factors like <strong>fibrinogen, factor VIII, factor XIII, and von Willebrand factor. </strong>It has minimal <strong>plasma and ABO antigens</strong>, <strong>reducing the risk of ABO incompatibility reactions.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option A. Fresh frozen plasma:</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"> FFP contains all<strong> coagulation factors</strong>, including soluble <strong>ABO antigens</strong>. <strong>ABO incompatibility </strong>can lead to <strong>hemolytic reactions</strong>; thus, it should be <strong>matched </strong>with the <strong>recipient&#39;s blood group</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option B. Platelet-rich plasma:</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"> PRP is derived from <strong>whole blood and retains the ABO antigens</strong>. Transfusion with<strong> incompatible PRP </strong>can also lead to<strong> hemolytic reactions.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option C. Single donor platelets:</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"> Single donor platelets carry the<strong> donor&#39;s ABO antigens</strong>, and while the risk is <strong>lower compared to red cell transfusion, ABO compatibility </strong>is still preferred to minimize the risk of reaction.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong> </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">While <strong>ABO matching </strong>is ideal for all <strong>blood components</strong>, <strong>cryoprecipitate </strong>is the least likely to cause an<strong> ABO incompatibility reaction </strong>due to its<strong> low content of plasma </strong>and <strong>ABO antigens</strong>. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Wintrobes 12<sup>th</sup> /850</span></strong></span></span></p>",
